{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DWVqA5hkAKPQXmKiFJUMTs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the setup:\n\n1. **Elasticsearch 8.11.1** running as 3-node StatefulSet\n2. **MinIO** running as a Deployment\n3. The `es-secure-settings` Secret contains:\n   - `s3.client.default.access_key`: `minioadmin`\n   - `s3.client.default.secret_key`: `minioadmin`\n4. The ConfigMap has the S3 endpoint configured in `elasticsearch.yml` (but credentials shouldn't be there, they're in the keystore)\n5. The StatefulSet mounts the secret at `/mnt/secure-settings` - but this is NOT the right way to load secure settings into Elasticsearch. \n\nThe real problem is that Elasticsearch reads secure settings from its own keystore file (`/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/elasticsearch.keystore`), not from mounted directories. To properly inject these S3 credentials, I need to either use the `elasticsearch-keystore` CLI tool to add them to each pod's keystore, or leverage the Elasticsearch Keystore API to set them dynamically. The mounted secret files won't automatically load into the keystore, so I need to use `kubectl exec` to add the credentials from those files to each pod's keystore, then trigger a reload of the secure settings across the cluster.\n\nWriting shell commands... I need to verify the S3 plugin is installed and check the keystore status in each pod, then work through adding the credentials, reloading the secure settings, registering the snapshot repository, and finally creating a snapshot.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3937,"cache_read_input_tokens":29530,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3937},"output_tokens":31,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_